      <p>
        <alert>In general, I am not primarily interested in your final answers—I am far more concerned with your ability to clearly demonstrate an understanding of the process that leads to those answers.</alert>
        This emphasis on process is intentional: it reflects the reality that in real-world problem solving, especially in STEM fields, knowing how to arrive at a correct solution is just as important—if not more so—than the solution itself. For this reason, I provide final answers for most out-of-class practice problem sets, so you can focus your effort on understanding the steps that lead to those solutions.
      </p>
      <p>On quizzes and exams, partial credit will be minimal unless you include clear, valid, and logical supporting work. I want to see how you reason through a problem, not just whether you can arrive at the right number.</p>
      <p>Additionally, while not all techniques we study in this course will be equally relevant to every student—given the diverse majors represented in Calculus II—the foundational mathematical skills you develop will remain relevant in all future STEM courses. Demonstrating fluency with these core skills—such as algebraic manipulation, mathematical reasoning, and structured problem-solving—not only reinforces your conceptual understanding now but also builds a toolkit you’ll continue to rely on as problems become more complex and domain-specific.</p>
      <p>Ultimately, my goal is to help you build both confidence and competence in your problem-solving process, which is a transferable skill across all scientific and technical disciplines.</p>
    </introduction>
